","1515":"1515","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Drax, Yorkshire, England":"Drax, Yorkshire, England","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1455–7 February 1515":"1455–7 February 1515","1455–1515":"1455–1515","1460–1489":"1460–1489","1477–Female":"1477–Deceased","1487–1540":"1487–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Deceased","1427–1501":"1427–1501","1431–1511":"1431–1511","7 February 1515":"7 February 1515","10 August 1501":"10 August 1501","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","after 1489":"after 1489","1501":"1501","1511":"1511","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1487":"1487","1486":"1486","1431":"1431","1540":"1540","1427":"1427","1515":"1515","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Drax, Yorkshire, England":"Drax, Yorkshire, England","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drakes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Drake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Drax (Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>dræg</i> ‘portage, place where boats are dragged’ or <i>dræg</i> ‘drag net’, influenced by Old Norse <i>drag</i> ‘portage’, with a plural <i>drages</i> being shortened to <i>drags</i>, <i>Drax</i>.","In some cases perhaps an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) cognate in some other language."],"variants":[{"name":"Drake","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>drake</i>, either ‘drake, male duck’ (compare   Duck  ) or ‘dragon’ (Old English <i>draca</i> ‘snake, dragon’ or the cognate Old Norse <i>draki</i>), including an emblematic dragon on a flag (compare   Dragon  ). Both the Old English and the Old Norse forms are from Latin <i>draco</i> ‘snake, monster’; its sense as a nickname is unclear but it may have had the sense ‘standard bearer’. The name was taken to Ireland in the 13th century and reinforced by later English settlers in the 17th century.","German: from Low German <i>drake</i> ‘dragon’, familiar as image on signboards, hence a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn with such signboard.","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized and Flemish, of <b>Draak</b>, a cognate of 2 above, from <i>draak</i> (Middle Dutch <i>drake</i>) ‘dragon’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":0,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Drakes was born in 1455, in Drax, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Alexander Drakes of Woodhall, was 28 and his mother, Rosanna Jane Wortley, was 24. He married Margaret Amias in 1486, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 7 February 1515, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1455–7 February 1515":"1455–7. veebruar 1515","1455–1515":"1455–1515","1460–1489":"1460–1489","1477–Female":"1477–Surnud","1487–1540":"1487–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Su